# Story Milestones

## Before machine is built

The team's work is considered quackery by their university. There should be early scenes of them being laughed off of university resources — denied lab space, equipment access, or funding by skeptical faculty or administrators. (human)

Early in the story, show the audience examples of important laws of physics before those laws get broken later. For example, demonstrate conservation of energy clearly before the machine violates it. Don't rely on the audience already knowing these laws in advance. (human)

Have some dialog early in the movie talking about the physics of light waves and quantum effects, with lines like "we don't really know how they work" and "all we can do is just measure it, and make some guesses at how it works." (human)

Have examples of thinking about dimensions being represented in a flattened way, like elevation lines on a map. (human)


## Selfish use of the machine

While the characters are advancing the science of the machine (and being very "by the book" about its safety), they also start using the machine selfishly to overcome bureaucracy and plot obstacles — keeping the funding of the machine going. (human)

Example: Some boss character is about to drive away and enforce some hindrance on the team. So the characters teleport a chunk of the boss's engine block into the machine, disabling the car. (human)

These moments of random carved-out chunks of objects appearing in the machine provide comedic levity between the very academic, heady, math-type experiments. (human)

